<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.time.com/time/magazine/a...-471198,00.html">www.time.com/time/magazin...98,00.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.cis.org/articles/2002/back1302.html">www.cis.org/articles/2002/back1302.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Immigration has become the determinate factor in population growth. The arrival of 1.5 million immigrants each year, coupled with 750,000 births to immigrant women annually, means that immigration policy is adding over two million people to the U.S. population each year, accounting for at least two-thirds of U.S. population growth.<br>
<br>
U.S. companies are expected to send 3.3 million jobs overseas in the next 12 years, primarily to India, according to a study by Forrester Research. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1655<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/2/03 9:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=168.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Where the Good Jobs Are Going</span><hr size=1> Your Time link doesn't work btw.<br>
<br>
Well, there are 2 separate issues here.<br>
<br>
1) Allowing immigration to the United States.<br>
2) Outsourcing jobs to foreign markets.<br>
<br>
I support increasing immigration limits.  Immigration has no detrimental effect on the labor situation.  If you add 100 immigrants, and they all get jobs, they spend money in the economy and their spending generates 100 more jobs.  It's a wash overall, immigration does not cause job shortages, that's a myth.  If an immigrant wants to come to the US and not work, he shouldn't be eligible for welfare or other government programs.  That would be a substantial drain on the economy.  Working immigrants however are no problem.<br>
<br>
Second, outsourcing jobs to foreign countries is a matter of what is economically best for a company.  The effects are complicated.  For the most part, we transfer only the crappiest jobs overseas (factory work, other unskilled labor, etc) and we maintain the highest paying service oriented jobs in our own country.  This has a positive effect on the economy and on the wealth of America.  It involves the financial concept of leverage.  Say I have 100 dollars.  I leverage the money to 1000 dollars and invest that at a 10 percent return and pay 5 percent interest.  I end up with 150 dollars, or a 50% return.  On the other hand, Say I just invested the money without leverage.  I would make 10 dollars, a 10% return.  It's the same idea with corporations.  Americans can make more money and have higher paying jobs because we leverage with unskilled foreign workers.  It adds to our wealth, not the other way around.  Companies are by and large American owned, and this means increased profits to the stockholders as well, which is extra money that flows into our economy.  That generates more jobs and fuels the economy.<br>
<br>
If you happen to be working in a factory that gets moved overseas, you're probably going to suffer as a result.  However, many Americans will gain small benefits from the move, and overall, there is a net benefit to America.<br>
<br>
You are making common economic mistakes.  Some things seem to make sense intuitively, but are not correct.<br>
<br>
