<br>
Money going to walmart and mcdonalds helps us all out.  (Not to mention that I've spent my share of time at McDonald's and wouldn't have any problem shopping at Walmart.)  Your views of the economy are too narrow and selective.  Money goes to walmart, it helps the stockholders and employees of walmart, they go out and spend the money, it then gets diffused to thousands of businesses, which in turn generates new jobs and helps you.  Also, immigrants pay taxes, and due to economies of scale, that helps you out.  If we add a million people, we don't need a bigger military, yet it's more people to spread the cost over.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Also, the way you're &quot;leaning&quot; towards, Ammelen, helps CEOs but what about people like you and me?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Again, you don't understand how this works.  Money going into the economy helps *everyone*.  The effects are very broad and cannot be isolated to one group or class of people.  Money going to the wealthy means more investment capital, more entrepreneurialism, and the creation of new businesses and thus new jobs.  It provides liquid capital in our economy and that is critical to finance businesses in the tech industry that employ people like you.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There is no company loyalty like there used to be in the 50s. Do you really like knowing the fact you may lose your job at any given moment?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think this is better.  It encourages performance and makes people work harder.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think it's more about that extra personal jet or new hummer then about going under for many companies.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
More capital means expansion and greater spending, again feeding the economy.  Buying a new jet or a new hummer means more money to the companies that makes those, thus providing more jobs.  You underestimate how interrelated it all is.  People do things for selfish reasons in capitalism, the beauty of the system is that it takes greed and allows it to profit the society as a whole.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;Immigrants sending record sums of cash home to Mexico<br>
About $10 billion transferred across border during ï¿½02 &quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It's peanuts really in comparison to the size of the American economy.  America gives multiples of that in foreign aid every year.  A large portion of that money ends up getting spent on American goods exported to other countries anyways.  Finally, the global economy is extremely interconnected, good economies across the globe are in all of our best interests.<br>
<br>
What's the difference in your mind between your ancestors who were immigrants and those immigrants who come to America today and work their asses off for a fresh start?  How can you deny them the opportunities your family had?  I can understand being angry at people that come over asking for handouts, but those people don't take jobs anyways, so they can't be the ones you're talking about.<br>
