I don't claim to be an expert here.  I do understand that by companies saving money, that does pump more growth into our economy supposedly.  But it still has the potential to be a detrimental cycle. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=misscheivous>MissCheivous</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 42<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/3/03 11:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=168.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Where the Good Jobs Are Going</span><hr size=1> My hometown <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>was</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a factory town. Everything was made there from furiture to nylons. Now, since NAFTA, virtually the the factories have packed up and moved to Mexico. Now Ammelen, you may say that this was better for the economy as a whole, but what I see is an increase in crime, unemployment, people losing thier homes, and people having to move to a different community to find work. My fathers job moved south of the border and yes he found another line of work, but he was only a few years shy of retireing. And his retirement package was severely cut. NAFTA was signed quite a while back and my poor hometown has still not recovered. And with all the young people leaving to find work it is dying slowly. Thousands of people lost thier jobs, sometimes it was 4000 at a shot. And nothing was brought back into our community to aliviate the situation. So yes I do have a problem with that. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.comcast.net/~dremarian/wsb/media/68398/site1036.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
